00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:28.200
PROFESSOR: We have
the privilege today

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:30.300
of hearing from
Professor Susan Silbey.

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:33.120
Professor Silbey
taught this class

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:37.230
with Professor [? Dysart ?]
and me in the last two years.

00:00:37.230 --> 00:00:42.690
And she is a sociologist,
political scientist,

00:00:42.690 --> 00:00:46.920
anthropologist, head of
the anthropology section.

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:50.220
And obviously brings a
different perspective

00:00:50.220 --> 00:00:56.010
to a number of these issues than
I, a poor country economist do.

00:00:56.010 --> 00:00:58.710
And as I said last
time, I showed

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:01.980
you a little bit of the
economics of energy demand,

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:05.220
and then suggested at
the end of the lecture,

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:08.950
by talking about
dollars on the sidewalk

00:01:08.950 --> 00:01:12.240
and what picked up in energy
efficiency on the one hand,

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:15.330
and people aggressively
investing in energy

00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:17.800
efficiency on the other hand.

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:21.720
Perhaps, the notion of
tangible energy services

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:26.490
wasn't quite rich enough
to explain energy demand.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:29.880
And now, it will
all be explained.

00:01:29.880 --> 00:01:35.590
SUSAN SILBEY: Well, Hello,
it's rather a tall order.

00:01:35.590 --> 00:01:37.230
But we'll try.

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:41.460
On Monday, Dick talked to
you about the economics

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:43.260
of energy demand.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:47.490
He talked about how
demand for energy

00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:52.170
is derived from demand
for products and services.

00:01:52.170 --> 00:01:54.960
And so we talk
about it as mediated

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:58.290
or derived demand, which
requires some adjustments

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:01.410
in the basic economic models.

00:02:01.410 --> 00:02:04.320
He also mentioned, I
believe, that variations

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:10.020
in derived demand depend upon
fixed capital investments, as

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:14.640
well as short and
long run expectations.

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:20.160
And that, because of those
short and long run expectations,

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:23.250
income and price
elasticities are generally

00:02:23.250 --> 00:02:27.240
limited, unlike in other
products and services,

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:29.970
and thus, constraining
the ability

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:34.060
to maximize with
efficient responses.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:35.940
And as Dick just
mentioned again,

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:41.130
people do not always maximize
or optimize, let me say,

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:42.180
their decisions.

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:44.160
There's lots of
possible efficiencies

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.240
that are not pursued.

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:48.990
And he mentioned, I believe,
on Monday, the leaving

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:51.750
those dollars on the sidewalk.

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:54.990
Because of, perhaps,
imperfect information,

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:58.830
riskiness and uncertainty
of future savings,

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:01.470
could be a lot of
other reasons too.

00:03:01.470 --> 00:03:03.780
And as he mentioned
again, just now,

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:06.630
people might be over investing.

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:09.540
Now, let's think
about what that means.

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:13.380
To over invest in efficiency
means, by economic models,

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:19.050
you're not going to get
a specific dollar return,

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:20.640
the Prius being example.

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:25.710
But there might be other
reasons why people might do it.

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:32.310
That is go for more efficiency
than is defined economically.

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:37.200
So why do we see economically
non-optimal decisions?

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:40.200
That's the $64,000 question.

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:42.090
How do people act?

00:03:42.090 --> 00:03:45.040
Why do people do what they do?

00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:47.730
Why are they not, in
the economic model,

00:03:47.730 --> 00:03:50.910
perfectly rational actors?

00:03:50.910 --> 00:03:54.000
Now, it is the mission
of all of social science

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.050
to try to describe
human behavior.

00:03:58.050 --> 00:04:02.550
But the explanations
that come from economics

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:05.280
are not necessarily
the same that come

00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:07.380
from the other social sciences.

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:11.970
How many of you have had
a course in economics

00:04:11.970 --> 00:04:14.230
before this one?

00:04:14.230 --> 00:04:17.408
Oh, lots of you, because it's
required for this course.

00:04:17.408 --> 00:04:17.950
That's right.

00:04:17.950 --> 00:04:19.390
But I didn't see every hand.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:23.890
I was wondering how accurate
this survey was going to be.

00:04:23.890 --> 00:04:28.720
How many of you have had
a political science class?

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:29.840
Let me see those hands.

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:34.720
I can't see, one, two,
three, four, five, six.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:37.780
How many-- oh did I
miss some over here?

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:38.860
Seven, eight.

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:41.935
OK, how many have
had a history class?

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:46.710
Wow, that's pretty good.

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:52.470
How many have had an
anthropology class?

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:53.930
Zero, right?

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:56.790
Oh, one, two.

00:04:56.790 --> 00:05:01.170
And we don't offer sociology
here for undergraduates, only

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:04.570
really for graduate students.

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:09.830
So this-- why do
people do what they do?

00:05:09.830 --> 00:05:13.680
It turns out that each
of the social sciences

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:17.370
has a slightly different answer.

00:05:17.370 --> 00:05:21.000
And so by way of, well,
for those of you who

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.380
have had a political
science class, how is it

00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:27.360
different from economics?

00:05:31.330 --> 00:05:34.052
Nobody wants-- Yeah, Andrew?

00:05:34.052 --> 00:05:36.890
AUDIENCE: No, equations
and stuff like that.

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:39.540
SUSAN SILBEY: Well, that
turns out not to be true.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:42.680
It just isn't in the--

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:45.080
it's just not in the
undergraduate class.

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:46.800
There are plenty of equations.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:49.340
There are plenty of
equations in sociology, too,

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:51.660
not in anthropology.

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:54.510
OK, so maybe I need to do this.

00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:57.020
So if you think of
the social sciences

00:05:57.020 --> 00:06:02.130
as the study of human behavior,
there is a division of labor.

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:05.510
Now, this division of labor
can be simply explained,

00:06:05.510 --> 00:06:10.190
but gets a little complicated
when you go into detail.

00:06:10.190 --> 00:06:14.570
So we might think of the
most basic and simplest

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:18.320
social science as
psychology, which we almost

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:20.540
don't have anymore,
which is about

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:24.950
what goes on inside
people's heads.

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:29.810
Psychology being the
study of a person,

00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:36.380
and explaining what this
person does by looking inside.

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:42.020
And we have various terms for
talking about what's inside

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:45.410
people's heads, their desires,
we talk about the id, which

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:49.550
is the desires you have, and
the ego, which is the control,

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:53.910
and the notion of a
constraint on what you do.

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:55.190
But then we have--

00:06:55.190 --> 00:07:00.980
and I would put psychology
by itself as different

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:03.590
from the rest of
the social sciences.

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:08.360
And then we have
sociology, which

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:11.690
says that it is
interested in what

00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:17.930
goes on between two or more
persons, never a person alone.

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:22.610
And the unit of analysis, or
the subject, is the interaction.

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:26.840
Not what's in here,
but what is exchanged

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:28.800
between the two of them.

00:07:28.800 --> 00:07:31.160
Now, some people would
say that sociology

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:33.680
is the queen, because
everything follows

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:36.260
from these interactions.

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.590
Because the interactions
can take various patterns.

00:07:39.590 --> 00:07:44.750
So they can be interactions
about production

00:07:44.750 --> 00:07:47.390
and distribution.

00:07:47.390 --> 00:07:49.412
And then we get economics.

00:07:52.550 --> 00:07:55.400
If you can think about
it as the interactions

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:58.130
where some people
are making things

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:00.500
that other people are receiving.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:04.400
And it happens through this
thing called the market.

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:08.330
Which is sort of an
invisible black box.

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:11.540
Then we might have
interactions that have

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:14.870
to do with force, violence.

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:17.090
And when that's
concentrated, we call

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:22.160
that the state who has
a monopoly of force.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:24.050
And that's what political
science studies.

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:32.650
So here, we have
four social sciences

00:08:32.650 --> 00:08:41.020
leaving the study of the
circulation of the signs.

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:42.669
This one's more complicated.

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:44.230
That's probably
why only two of you

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:47.470
took the classes, because you
don't understand what it is.

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:53.140
But it's the circulation of the
signs and symbols among people.

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:56.350
And we call that culture.

00:08:56.350 --> 00:08:59.320
And that's what
anthropology studies,

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:01.600
the practices, and
the production,

00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:04.510
and circulation of signs.

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:07.330
So there you have
the social sciences.

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:10.720
Now, that's a very
simple, easy distinction.

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:16.660
But like most things in
life, that's too simple.

00:09:16.660 --> 00:09:21.580
And in any place--

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:23.470
oh, I forgot, you're
not supposed to.

00:09:23.470 --> 00:09:27.850
Oh, I forgot, I
forgot, I forgot.

00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:29.470
No human power here.

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:41.500
OK, so we have
political science, which

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:46.270
studies force and the state.

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:50.480
But it overlaps
with some sociology,

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:52.630
which looks at the
patterns of interactions.

00:09:52.630 --> 00:09:55.300
And there's something
called political sociology.

00:09:55.300 --> 00:10:01.150
And then some of sociology
studies production

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:02.350
and distribution.

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:05.050
And we call that
economic sociology.

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:10.690
And some of economics
is now interested in how

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:15.490
people's desires and behaviors
affect their decision making.

00:10:15.490 --> 00:10:18.820
We call that
behavioral economics.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:23.480
And that overlaps with
psychology and anthropology.

00:10:23.480 --> 00:10:25.000
So you might just
think about what

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.530
is actually studied as having
normal distributions that

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:30.640
overlap.

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:32.920
And depending--
lots of people are

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:37.990
studying in these places, which
we call interdisciplinary.

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:40.480
And that's how you
get a class like this.

00:10:40.480 --> 00:10:47.650
OK, so why do people,
or how do people--

00:10:47.650 --> 00:10:53.950
how do people deal with
these questions about energy?

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:56.270
How do they make the decisions?

00:10:56.270 --> 00:11:01.090
So what I'm going to try to do
today, and this is my outline,

00:11:01.090 --> 00:11:05.200
is to go through
some basic models,

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:09.430
some very general models, about
how people make decisions,

00:11:09.430 --> 00:11:13.960
the variations and the
motives, we might say,

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:16.480
or the vocabularies of motive.

00:11:16.480 --> 00:11:19.300
I'm going to look
at some results

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:24.010
from cognitive science and
sociology of decision making,

00:11:24.010 --> 00:11:26.380
going to look at
a few experiments.

00:11:26.380 --> 00:11:29.320
And then, maybe, we can
end, if time permits,

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:32.890
with some discussion
of what happens

00:11:32.890 --> 00:11:35.590
when we focus on the
individual and the ironies

00:11:35.590 --> 00:11:36.970
of popular psychology.

00:11:36.970 --> 00:11:38.470
I'm not sure we'll get there.

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:40.510
In future classes,
I know you are

00:11:40.510 --> 00:11:43.480
going to discuss
decision making in firms

00:11:43.480 --> 00:11:47.530
and organizations, which
are aggregates, patterned

00:11:47.530 --> 00:11:48.640
aggregates.

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:51.730
Not one, but the pattern
by which people are

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:54.350
arranged in their activities.

00:11:54.350 --> 00:11:56.590
Those are organizations
and firms.

00:11:56.590 --> 00:11:59.450
And we will look at
states, or you will,

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:03.250
in which we make
public policies.

00:12:03.250 --> 00:12:10.580
So how do people make decisions?

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:15.400
How do we make decisions
about right and wrong?

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.620
What kind of car to buy?

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:22.810
Why are people buying that
Prius even though they'll never

00:12:22.810 --> 00:12:23.875
recoup the savings?

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:35.790
Why do we think that skinny
women are beautiful now?

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.550
And 100 years ago, we
thought that heavy women

00:12:38.550 --> 00:12:40.380
were beautiful?

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:43.616
Maybe none of you know
that that was the case?

00:12:43.616 --> 00:12:45.270
AUDIENCE: Advertising.

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:47.210
SUSAN SILBEY: OK, advertising.

00:12:56.250 --> 00:12:58.530
Why might that-- but what
about the advertising?

00:12:58.530 --> 00:13:01.350
What did the advertising say?

00:13:01.350 --> 00:13:03.660
And was it advertising
100 years ago?

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:08.140
Yeah.

00:13:08.140 --> 00:13:10.930
AUDIENCE: There's
some predominately--

00:13:10.930 --> 00:13:12.940
fashion advertising
of the '50s and '60s

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:17.185
switched from more
volumptuous sexual icon

00:13:17.185 --> 00:13:19.050
to something really skinny.

00:13:19.050 --> 00:13:20.700
There's one person
in particular named

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:25.100
Twiggy who kind of became a
very famous, very skinny fashion

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:25.600
model.

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:27.370
And everyhting from
that kind of followed.

00:13:27.370 --> 00:13:29.530
SUSAN SILBEY: Yeah, but it
was in the 19th century,

00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:31.360
before there was advertising.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:34.014
Yes, David.

00:13:34.014 --> 00:13:37.140
AUDIENCE: I'd say there's
also a change in the signaling

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:41.440
about what you're buying.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:44.300
If you go further
back, there are

00:13:44.300 --> 00:13:47.680
depictions of larger, heavier
people as being wealthy,

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:50.000
which is something [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.120
Which was, you didn't
have to work in fields.

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:53.620
You had enough to eat.

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:55.975
[INAUDIBLE]

00:13:55.975 --> 00:13:57.100
SUSAN SILBEY: That's right.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:01.840
And the signaling was,
in the 19th century,

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:04.990
to have heft on you meant
you were wealthy enough

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:06.010
to eat well.

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:08.090
Because most people did not.

00:14:08.090 --> 00:14:10.520
So this is just a
little exercise.

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:12.430
And this is about culture.

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:16.660
This is about the circulating
signs, the signaling.

00:14:16.660 --> 00:14:18.820
So you've all got it.

00:14:18.820 --> 00:14:19.540
You got it.

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:23.740
The culture encourages
us to want certain things

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:26.170
to think their beautiful.

00:14:26.170 --> 00:14:27.550
Is there anything else?

00:14:27.550 --> 00:14:29.590
None of you believe--

00:14:29.590 --> 00:14:31.140
AUDIENCE: Education as well.

00:14:31.140 --> 00:14:35.300
SUSAN SILBEY: You're all so
socialized, it's fantastic.

