00:23:04.260 --> 00:23:08.010
Oh, Gandhi was charismatic.

00:23:08.010 --> 00:23:09.940
These are the
explanations that say

00:23:09.940 --> 00:23:13.560
there is something
about the person that

00:23:13.560 --> 00:23:18.190
produces the behavior
and the achievements.

00:23:18.190 --> 00:23:21.510
The alternative-- and
so, OK, so they're

00:23:21.510 --> 00:23:24.450
unique and independent
individuals.

00:23:24.450 --> 00:23:32.110
And society is merely the
aggregate of these individuals.

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:38.260
The philosophers and writers
who exemplify this point of view

00:23:38.260 --> 00:23:42.130
include John Locke
in the 17th century,

00:23:42.130 --> 00:23:46.720
John Stuart Mill in the 19th
century, Friedrich Hayek

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:50.140
and Milton Friedman
in the 20th century.

00:23:50.140 --> 00:23:53.170
OK, when you come
across these names,

00:23:53.170 --> 00:23:55.480
you can now put
them in the box that

00:23:55.480 --> 00:24:01.150
says we can explain what
happens in the world, including

00:24:01.150 --> 00:24:03.550
the production and
distribution of energy

00:24:03.550 --> 00:24:06.470
by looking at
individual behavior.

00:24:06.470 --> 00:24:09.340
And that's what we're
going to do today.

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:14.020
But there's a second answer,
or a second kind theory,

00:24:14.020 --> 00:24:16.640
which many of you
gave me to start with,

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:21.670
which is that the motives and
the intentions of individuals

00:24:21.670 --> 00:24:26.440
are located in a
larger circulation,

00:24:26.440 --> 00:24:30.070
whether it's advertising
or education,

00:24:30.070 --> 00:24:33.700
that people anticipate
certain things to happen.

00:24:33.700 --> 00:24:36.950
That they locate
themselves in a sequence.

00:24:36.950 --> 00:24:41.170
And so that it's
not the individual,

00:24:41.170 --> 00:24:44.500
but it's what the
individual has learned

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:48.040
over time, and the experiences
that they have had,

00:24:48.040 --> 00:24:53.110
and what the philosopher John
Dewey called situated action.

00:24:53.110 --> 00:24:55.900
That an action
doesn't mean the same

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:58.100
in one place as in another.

00:24:58.100 --> 00:25:03.400
And so therefore, the
action you make or do

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:05.960
isn't the same in
one place or another.

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:08.590
And if you take account
of that variation,

00:25:08.590 --> 00:25:11.900
then it isn't the
individual causation.

00:25:11.900 --> 00:25:14.120
But it's also the situation.

00:25:14.120 --> 00:25:17.650
And the authors who say
these kinds of things

00:25:17.650 --> 00:25:19.900
include Pierre Bourdieu.

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:24.250
And he calls this situation,
or these culturally

00:25:24.250 --> 00:25:29.290
learned behaviors,
habits, or the habitus.

00:25:29.290 --> 00:25:33.430
And Adam Smith, in his Theory
of Moral Sentiments, which

00:25:33.430 --> 00:25:38.730
he wrote before he wrote The
Wealth of Nations in 1776,

00:25:38.730 --> 00:25:42.990
do you all know The Wealth
of Nations, 1776, OK,

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:45.870
and you all know about
the invisible hand.

00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:48.210
OK, yes, no?

00:25:48.210 --> 00:25:51.960
Well, look it up on Wikipedia.

00:25:51.960 --> 00:25:56.490
But what is important about that
theory, which most people take

00:25:56.490 --> 00:25:59.880
as obvious, because the
foundation of the market

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:02.790
is that before he wrote
The Wealth of Nations he,

00:26:02.790 --> 00:26:05.640
wrote The Theory of
Moral Sentiments.

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:09.450
And in that book,
what Adam Smith said

00:26:09.450 --> 00:26:14.340
is that the person all
people will try to be good.

00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:18.030
They will be limited
in their desires, which

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:21.630
is what gets translated
into demand in the market

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:29.620
by the expectation of what their
neighbors will think of them.

00:26:29.620 --> 00:26:32.320
That doesn't hold very
true in the modern world,

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:34.690
except if you go
to what some of you

00:26:34.690 --> 00:26:36.670
start at the
beginning, advertising,

00:26:36.670 --> 00:26:38.900
and signaling, and education.

00:26:38.900 --> 00:26:42.130
So what we desire,
Adam Smith said,

00:26:42.130 --> 00:26:45.010
will be constrained
by what we think

00:26:45.010 --> 00:26:47.050
our neighbors will think of us.

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:52.300
And that's the framework in
which our desires or demands

00:26:52.300 --> 00:26:54.880
can shape a market.

00:26:54.880 --> 00:27:00.010
So in this second
bifurcated notion,

00:27:00.010 --> 00:27:02.620
it's not that history
makes the man.

00:27:02.620 --> 00:27:06.480
It's that man makes history.

00:27:06.480 --> 00:27:09.240
No, no, I said it backwards.

00:27:09.240 --> 00:27:10.860
Erase that.

00:27:10.860 --> 00:27:13.830
The second theory,
history makes the man.

00:27:13.830 --> 00:27:21.500
So Barack Obama can
get elected in 2008.

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:29.930
He could not have gotten elected
president in 1980, or 1990,

00:27:29.930 --> 00:27:31.640
or 2000.

00:27:31.640 --> 00:27:36.140
Conditions had to be such,
is how the story would go.

00:27:36.140 --> 00:27:41.780
Or that George Washington
would have been a farmer,

00:27:41.780 --> 00:27:44.630
and he would have spent
his whole life as a farmer,

00:27:44.630 --> 00:27:49.220
were it not for the
American Revolution,

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:53.240
which he did not participate
in until the war started.

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:56.060
He was not one of the
signers of the Declaration

00:27:56.060 --> 00:27:57.650
of Independence.

00:27:57.650 --> 00:28:00.530
They needed someone
to be a general.

00:28:00.530 --> 00:28:03.480
Without that need, he wouldn't
have been the president.

00:28:03.480 --> 00:28:10.040
And so this second model is
that personhood, identity, will,

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:17.000
the desires are produced and are
contingent on the opportunities

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.340
that exist, and the constraints.

00:28:19.340 --> 00:28:21.870
And the authors who write
from this perspective

00:28:21.870 --> 00:28:24.620
are Max Weber, Emile
[? Durkheim ?] Karl

00:28:24.620 --> 00:28:28.310
Polanyi, Karl Marx,
Jean-Jacques Rousseau.

00:28:28.310 --> 00:28:30.650
So when you encounter
those names,

00:28:30.650 --> 00:28:35.810
you can put them as antithesis
to Locke, Mill, Hayek,

00:28:35.810 --> 00:28:37.050
and Friedman.

00:28:37.050 --> 00:28:40.430
OK, now, I'll put in
a little amendment

00:28:40.430 --> 00:28:41.900
that's not in the notes.

00:28:41.900 --> 00:28:44.750
That for the most
part, Americans,

00:28:44.750 --> 00:28:47.810
when you survey
them and ask them

00:28:47.810 --> 00:28:52.430
why things happen as they do,
they give you the first answer.

00:28:52.430 --> 00:28:54.990
Because people are special.

00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:56.840
That's why what they have.

00:28:56.840 --> 00:28:59.540
Or that's why things turn
out the way they are.

00:28:59.540 --> 00:29:04.340
We are, in the United States,
a nation of individualists.

00:29:04.340 --> 00:29:09.320
We rarely see the
patterns of aggregation.

00:29:09.320 --> 00:29:21.780
So now, one more, one more
how do people make decisions.

00:29:25.410 --> 00:29:27.840
There's one more
model that I'd like

00:29:27.840 --> 00:29:31.440
to present to you, that's
not a binary model.

00:29:31.440 --> 00:29:33.600
These have been binaries, right?

00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:37.620
Two different views, individual,
biological, collective

00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:40.110
and culture.

00:29:40.110 --> 00:29:43.380
The sociologist Max
Weber offered us

00:29:43.380 --> 00:29:45.780
a more complex notion.

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:50.100
He suggested that
action is social

00:29:50.100 --> 00:29:52.650
whenever we take account
of somebody else,

00:29:52.650 --> 00:29:55.830
just like Adam Smith's
notion of the moral person.

00:29:55.830 --> 00:29:58.740
We care what our
neighbors think.

00:29:58.740 --> 00:30:02.250
Now, Weber didn't say we care
what our neighbors think.

00:30:02.250 --> 00:30:15.310
He merely said that he will
define action as social when

00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:19.640
we take account of another,
when there's more than one.

00:30:19.640 --> 00:30:24.100
And we anticipate,
or we care, or we

00:30:24.100 --> 00:30:29.380
want to say something
about or imagine an other

00:30:29.380 --> 00:30:31.120
in relationship to ourselves.

00:30:31.120 --> 00:30:32.590
That's what makes it social.

00:30:32.590 --> 00:30:34.420
So whenever you hear
the word "social,"

00:30:34.420 --> 00:30:37.120
which is bandied about
something terrible,

00:30:37.120 --> 00:30:41.240
it always means an
interaction of two or more.

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:46.540
And in his grand theory, which
I'll try to do in five minutes,

00:30:46.540 --> 00:30:51.970
this is 1,000 pages, OK, you're
getting it in five minutes,

00:30:51.970 --> 00:30:55.270
there are four ways
in which we can

00:30:55.270 --> 00:30:58.030
take account of other people.

00:30:58.030 --> 00:31:02.080
The first one is what he
called rational action.

00:31:02.080 --> 00:31:06.820
And here, we have exactly
the economic model.

00:31:06.820 --> 00:31:11.830
That people act
and make decisions

00:31:11.830 --> 00:31:17.710
on the basis of reasoning,
of means and ends reasoning.

00:31:17.710 --> 00:31:22.900
That they take account of the
objects in the external world,

00:31:22.900 --> 00:31:24.370
the situations.

00:31:24.370 --> 00:31:27.100
They mobilize logic.

00:31:27.100 --> 00:31:31.390
And they try to figure out
how to get from here to there.

00:31:31.390 --> 00:31:36.520
They maximize their ends by
figuring out appropriate means.

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:39.950
This is our economic
rational actor model.

00:31:39.950 --> 00:31:44.170
And he called that
formal rational action.

00:31:44.170 --> 00:31:46.990
But he said there was
another kind of rationality,

00:31:46.990 --> 00:31:52.480
in which we were oriented
not to maximizing

00:31:52.480 --> 00:31:57.220
means ends efficiencies, but
because there was something

00:31:57.220 --> 00:32:01.150
we thought was good,
an absolute value.

00:32:01.150 --> 00:32:05.710
This could be a conscious
belief in a God, who tells us

00:32:05.710 --> 00:32:06.760
what to do.

00:32:06.760 --> 00:32:12.820
It could be some ethical value,
such as do unto others as you

00:32:12.820 --> 00:32:14.800
would have them do unto you.

00:32:14.800 --> 00:32:17.650
It could be aesthetic
to maximize beauty.

00:32:17.650 --> 00:32:21.160
It could be to
maximize equality,

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:28.280
as communism was originally
imagined by Karl Marx.

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:34.480
So that behavior is organized
to maximize or to fulfill

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:36.020
that absolute value.

00:32:36.020 --> 00:32:41.290
It's not an efficiency
or logical requirement

00:32:41.290 --> 00:32:43.270
of means and ends.

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:46.700
And the third kind of behavior--

00:32:46.700 --> 00:32:49.180
so this is virtue.

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:53.170
Could be you want to be
environmentally sustainable,

00:32:53.170 --> 00:32:55.550
whether it's efficient or not.

00:32:55.550 --> 00:32:59.080
OK, that's an alternative
to efficiency.

00:32:59.080 --> 00:33:02.740
The third kind of
behavior he described

00:33:02.740 --> 00:33:06.400
was ones which come from our
feelings, from our emotions.

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:11.270
We do things because
it feels good.

00:33:11.270 --> 00:33:13.000
Now, you all know
what that's like you

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.650
do a lot of that we all do.

00:33:15.650 --> 00:33:18.400
That's why people take
drugs, drink alcohol,

00:33:18.400 --> 00:33:22.060
have sex, because it feels good.

00:33:22.060 --> 00:33:25.660
It's also the basis
on which we sometimes

00:33:25.660 --> 00:33:27.790
convey honor to people.

00:33:27.790 --> 00:33:31.930
We say some people are
better than others.

00:33:31.930 --> 00:33:37.360
Being seen and celebrity,
this whole TV and internet

00:33:37.360 --> 00:33:41.710
world of being there,
people are getting some sort

00:33:41.710 --> 00:33:44.560
of emotional satisfaction.

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:48.820
And the fourth kind
of social action

00:33:48.820 --> 00:33:52.420
is simply tradition and habit.

00:33:52.420 --> 00:33:56.230
We act because we have
always done it this way.

00:33:56.230 --> 00:34:01.660
And that, sometimes, is a little
bit of mimicry, but mimicry

00:34:01.660 --> 00:34:05.620
of the past, rather than
necessarily something

00:34:05.620 --> 00:34:06.910
co-present.

00:34:06.910 --> 00:34:11.590
And there are lots of
societies, lots of groups.

00:34:11.590 --> 00:34:14.800
And this institution,
MIT, is frequently

00:34:14.800 --> 00:34:20.120
accused of being
stuck in its ways.

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:26.290
So when we were accredited a
few years ago, or re-accredited,

00:34:26.290 --> 00:34:28.510
the re-accreditation
committee said

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:33.850
that MIT had just about come
into the 20th century in terms

00:34:33.850 --> 00:34:37.540
of the information systems
in which it managed.

00:34:37.540 --> 00:34:40.810
We had hardly made it to
the end of the 20th century,

00:34:40.810 --> 00:34:43.659
because we don't change
things too easily.

00:34:43.659 --> 00:34:46.969
OK, habit, it's comfortable.

00:34:46.969 --> 00:34:57.620
So now, like those overlapping
disciplines, those overlapping

00:34:57.620 --> 00:35:01.730
disciplines, all these
concepts have fuzzy borders.

00:35:01.730 --> 00:35:07.430
So it's rare that you'll ever
find an empirically observable

00:35:07.430 --> 00:35:12.260
action social action that's
just one kind, that's just

00:35:12.260 --> 00:35:16.970
rational action, or that's
just affect without habit,

00:35:16.970 --> 00:35:17.990
or something else.

00:35:17.990 --> 00:35:22.130
And that brings us to exactly
where Dick left off on Monday.

00:35:22.130 --> 00:35:25.430
What else, besides
rational action,

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:32.570
besides economic reasoning might
be affecting demand for energy?

00:35:32.570 --> 00:35:38.150
OK, so these are the
basic models of--

00:35:38.150 --> 00:35:45.380
and habit, or
past, is what those

00:35:45.380 --> 00:35:50.840
are historic investments are
that we can't change very much.

00:35:50.840 --> 00:35:55.040
That we have suburbs
and automobiles.

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:58.520
That we have
habituated preferences

00:35:58.520 --> 00:36:01.340
in our political system
and the individualism

00:36:01.340 --> 00:36:06.110
that makes it very hard for us
to change our energy production

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:09.380
and consumption systems.

00:36:09.380 --> 00:36:15.010
So what I want-- this
is the big picture,

00:36:15.010 --> 00:36:18.360
and now, let's look at some
specific research that wants

00:36:18.360 --> 00:36:21.000
to do something with this.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.760
But I would like you to take
away from this the notion

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:28.290
that any human action
involves usually

00:36:28.290 --> 00:36:31.830
a combination of
these forms of action.

00:36:31.830 --> 00:36:33.360
These are the
categories which we

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:37.590
mix and match to describe it.

00:36:37.590 --> 00:36:41.460
So cognitive science
and the sociology

00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:48.270
of decisions, these days
there's been a recent marriage.

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:54.920
And it may, in the end, end up
being a marriage of our brain

00:36:54.920 --> 00:36:58.230
structure and our behavior.

00:36:58.230 --> 00:37:03.320
So what used to be
psychology, asking people

00:37:03.320 --> 00:37:06.710
why they do what they do,
watching them in experiments,

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:09.680
treating them just like
rats in experiments,

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:16.760
we now look inside their
brains with PET scans, fMRIs.

00:37:16.760 --> 00:37:22.000
The neuroscientists look at
the brains, the architecture

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:25.300
of our brains, the
arrangement of the pieces,

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:29.200
that's about all
they can do, so far.

00:37:29.200 --> 00:37:34.300
And look at the physical
matter inside our skulls,

00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:39.670
where the psychologist used to
study, we might say, the mind.

00:37:39.670 --> 00:37:41.890
Brain scientists
or neuroscientists

00:37:41.890 --> 00:37:43.240
study the brain.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:47.440
And the cognitive scientists
go, try to put the two together.

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:48.430
Is that fair?

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:52.580
Do we have any BCS majors here?

00:37:52.580 --> 00:37:54.602
Not a one?

00:37:54.602 --> 00:37:58.530
Not one brain and
cognitive science major.

00:37:58.530 --> 00:38:00.000
Interesting, I
would have thought

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.010
you'd all want to
become brain scientists.

00:38:02.010 --> 00:38:03.350
That's the future, folks.

00:38:06.570 --> 00:38:09.900
Well, do the brain and cognitive
science of energy decisions.

00:38:09.900 --> 00:38:13.650
There you go, there's
a dissertation for you.

00:38:13.650 --> 00:38:19.560
OK, so some of this
marriage of mind and brain

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:22.900
has produced some
interesting results.

00:38:22.900 --> 00:38:28.320
So that what people used
to think was hard wired,

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:32.610
the neuroscientists have
showed us is quite malleable.

00:38:32.610 --> 00:38:38.250
That in fact, oh, I think up
until about the 1980s, doctors

00:38:38.250 --> 00:38:41.280
and scientists would
say oh, well, you

00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:44.310
might be able to regenerate
muscles if you've

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:48.300
had an accident or damaged it.

00:38:48.300 --> 00:38:51.420
But the brain was what it
was and it never changed.

00:38:51.420 --> 00:38:54.430
Well, we know that's not true.

00:38:54.430 --> 00:38:57.310
Used to think it was
fixed and formed.

00:38:57.310 --> 00:39:00.280
But now, we know that
the neurons are always

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:01.150
in the making.

00:39:01.150 --> 00:39:03.970
And those circuits are changing.

00:39:03.970 --> 00:39:08.680
The neurons and networks,
we have learned,

00:39:08.680 --> 00:39:16.330
develop in response to
experience to the inputs.

00:39:16.330 --> 00:39:20.190
So that they shape
the capacity to act.

00:39:20.190 --> 00:39:24.500
So that it's not
just how you're born.

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:27.430
But the experiences
that you have had

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:30.390
transform your
mental capacities.

00:39:30.390 --> 00:39:31.820
Well, you all know that's true.

00:39:31.820 --> 00:39:33.980
You wouldn't have
gotten to MIT otherwise.

00:39:33.980 --> 00:39:37.220
Unless you all think there
was all these equations

00:39:37.220 --> 00:39:41.810
were in there to start with and
they just came out recently.

00:39:41.810 --> 00:39:43.280
That you've learned.

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:45.620
You've learned how to
defer gratification.

00:39:45.620 --> 00:39:48.650
That's what most successful
college students, to get here,

00:39:48.650 --> 00:39:49.790
you learned.

00:39:49.790 --> 00:39:54.830
And some people don't have the
experiences which allow that.

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:56.930
What if you're a
child who's never

00:39:56.930 --> 00:40:01.790
had gratification of any
bodily or emotional function?

00:40:01.790 --> 00:40:03.980
Well then delaying
it is not something

00:40:03.980 --> 00:40:07.400
you could learn that
will be rewarded.

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:09.450
You understand what I'm saying?

00:40:09.450 --> 00:40:13.550
So if you've never had a
full belly, then when food

00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:15.470
is put in front of you,
you're not necessarily

00:40:15.470 --> 00:40:18.750
going to wait to eat it
until you're told to eat it.

00:40:18.750 --> 00:40:19.830
It's as simple as that.

00:40:19.830 --> 00:40:23.150
And the same thing with
cognitive activities.

00:40:23.150 --> 00:40:25.070
So there's lots
of work now going

00:40:25.070 --> 00:40:30.340
on that is closing
the gap between what

00:40:30.340 --> 00:40:35.710
is observable between the inner
states and the external aspects

00:40:35.710 --> 00:40:37.700
of culture.

00:40:37.700 --> 00:40:43.800
So in this work, in
this scholarship,

00:40:43.800 --> 00:40:46.140
scholars, researchers,
have started

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:50.670
to distinguish a fundamental
difference between what

00:40:50.670 --> 00:40:56.700
they call automatic cognition
and deliberate cognition.

00:40:56.700 --> 00:41:01.650
Automatic cognition is rapid,
effortless, unintentional

00:41:01.650 --> 00:41:05.100
thoughts, things which are
those habits, those things we

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:06.690
do without thinking.

00:41:06.690 --> 00:41:09.750
And it allows quick
processing of information

00:41:09.750 --> 00:41:15.150
without extended thought
or figuring out what to do.

00:41:15.150 --> 00:41:20.700
Deliberate cognition is
slow, considered, measured.

00:41:20.700 --> 00:41:24.960
Where we can reject or
accept alternatives.

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:31.500
We can consider various
actions to take.

00:41:31.500 --> 00:41:35.970
Where we might actively
search for solutions,

00:41:35.970 --> 00:41:38.580
for characteristics,
for connections,

00:41:38.580 --> 00:41:41.700
for seeing if we can
find relationships.

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:47.670
And where we don't assume,
but we solve, you might say.

00:41:47.670 --> 00:41:53.400
So examples of
automatic cognition

00:41:53.400 --> 00:41:56.640
are as the example,
male and female.

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:59.490
We look at somebody and we
categorize them like that.

00:41:59.490 --> 00:42:03.150
When we can't categorize them
like that, we start to think.

00:42:03.150 --> 00:42:06.690
And we frequently, then,
refer to that person

00:42:06.690 --> 00:42:09.750
as not usual or not normal.

00:42:09.750 --> 00:42:12.870
Age, race, in the
United States is

00:42:12.870 --> 00:42:16.170
a fundamental
automatic cognition.

00:42:16.170 --> 00:42:19.640
Turns out not to be
that in all cultures.

00:42:19.640 --> 00:42:22.700
In many cultures,
it's much more varied.

00:42:22.700 --> 00:42:26.360
It's not a binary, like it
is in the United States.

00:42:26.360 --> 00:42:33.510
So our habits are examples
of automatic cognition.

00:42:33.510 --> 00:42:36.390
It's outside of our
thinking process.

00:42:36.390 --> 00:42:38.970
It's outside of consciousness.

00:42:38.970 --> 00:42:43.470
And it happens more often
when we're under stress.

00:42:43.470 --> 00:42:46.710
The experiments put people
in different conditions.

00:42:46.710 --> 00:42:50.970
And how quickly they respond
when they're under stress

00:42:50.970 --> 00:42:52.290
is measurable.

00:42:52.290 --> 00:42:55.710
In deliberate
cognition, what has

00:42:55.710 --> 00:43:00.300
been shown is that people
deliberate and they think

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:03.180
about alternatives
when there has been

00:43:03.180 --> 00:43:07.410
a disruption of those
habits, a disruption

00:43:07.410 --> 00:43:14.430
of non-thinking-- of
acting without thought.

00:43:14.430 --> 00:43:17.910
OK, so I want to give you
some empirical examples

00:43:17.910 --> 00:43:19.290
of how this works.

00:43:22.410 --> 00:43:27.420
The first example
is by Carol Heimer

00:43:27.420 --> 00:43:29.820
at Northwestern
University, where

00:43:29.820 --> 00:43:35.710
she did a study of neonatal
care in several hospitals.

00:43:35.710 --> 00:43:41.220
She noticed in these
wards for preemie babies

00:43:41.220 --> 00:43:44.850
that routines the
hospital had established

00:43:44.850 --> 00:43:47.430
were used to manage
what was a very

00:43:47.430 --> 00:43:50.460
uncertain medical
situation, very

00:43:50.460 --> 00:43:53.550
uncertain for the
families, very stressful.

00:43:53.550 --> 00:43:58.710
And that there was a very marked
hierarchy among the staff.

00:43:58.710 --> 00:44:02.850
The aides at the bottom,
the doctors at the top,

00:44:02.850 --> 00:44:07.080
the surgical nurses higher
up, others lower down.

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:11.430
And along with this
hierarchy of persons,

00:44:11.430 --> 00:44:16.080
Heimer also identified
a continuum of routines.

00:44:16.080 --> 00:44:18.390
At one end of her
spectrum, there

00:44:18.390 --> 00:44:22.200
were tasks which were
highly routinized.

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:26.410
That there was almost never any
variation for how it was done.

00:44:26.410 --> 00:44:28.530
And then there were
other tasks which

00:44:28.530 --> 00:44:33.120
varied a lot from patient to
patient and family to family.

00:44:33.120 --> 00:44:38.350
She noticed that when
there was either very, very

00:44:38.350 --> 00:44:43.510
routinized or very,
very unroutinized,

00:44:43.510 --> 00:44:46.360
that there was
deliberate cognition.

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:52.810
There was a great deal of talk,
examination, consideration

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:54.640
of alternatives.

00:44:54.640 --> 00:44:58.840
But where there was
moderate routinization,

00:44:58.840 --> 00:45:01.240
that things were automatic.

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:05.440
According to Heimer
the overroutinization

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:09.010
triggers deliberate
cognition, because people

00:45:09.010 --> 00:45:14.590
are so overwhelmed and
overloaded with routines

00:45:14.590 --> 00:45:20.890
that the things they have to
do routinely become a burden.

00:45:20.890 --> 00:45:25.030
They become noise,
rather than a signal.

00:45:25.030 --> 00:45:28.750
And they cease to focus
attention on the child

00:45:28.750 --> 00:45:30.430
or on the situation.

00:45:30.430 --> 00:45:34.900
Then because there's so many
things that need to be done,

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:39.538
and need to be done
in a specified way,

00:45:39.538 --> 00:45:43.090
they have to think
about how to do it.

00:45:43.090 --> 00:45:47.980
In underroutinized
context, they have

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:50.770
to figure out what to do
when there are no routines.

00:45:50.770 --> 00:45:52.510
And they have to be inductive.

00:45:52.510 --> 00:45:55.220
Is this like one we saw before?

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:58.660
Is this like the four
other cases last week?

00:45:58.660 --> 00:46:01.750
So that lots and
lots of routine,

00:46:01.750 --> 00:46:04.120
they have to think
about how to manage.

00:46:04.120 --> 00:46:06.310
No routine, they have to think.

00:46:06.310 --> 00:46:12.190
But simple, not high volume
of routines, and they

00:46:12.190 --> 00:46:13.630
act without thought.

00:46:13.630 --> 00:46:16.270
So that might be taking blood.

00:46:16.270 --> 00:46:20.210
It might be putting
in the injection.

00:46:20.210 --> 00:46:23.170
But if they have to do 10
of those things at once,

00:46:23.170 --> 00:46:24.800
then they will think about it.

00:46:24.800 --> 00:46:28.390
So that's one example.

00:46:28.390 --> 00:46:35.140
In a second study about
residents in an Argentinean

00:46:35.140 --> 00:46:40.540
shanty town, two scholars,
Auyero and Swistun

00:46:40.540 --> 00:46:44.050
studied the ways in which
people handled uncertainty

00:46:44.050 --> 00:46:50.410
in risk and especially the
conditions under which--

00:46:50.410 --> 00:46:53.410
the conditions which
sustained uncertainty

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:58.550
and sometimes led to assessments
of environmental pollutants.

00:46:58.550 --> 00:47:03.730
So they saw that sometimes,
people paid attention

00:47:03.730 --> 00:47:05.290
to the pollutants around them.

00:47:05.290 --> 00:47:06.730
And sometimes, they didn't.

00:47:06.730 --> 00:47:10.630
And they wanted to identify
those different situations.

00:47:10.630 --> 00:47:13.450
And the evidence they
collected suggested

00:47:13.450 --> 00:47:19.120
that if the polluters
pollute without disrupting

00:47:19.120 --> 00:47:24.040
the habits of the community,
the community paid no attention

00:47:24.040 --> 00:47:25.330
to the pollution.

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:28.730
But if the pollution
disrupted habits,

00:47:28.730 --> 00:47:31.180
such as getting
children to school,

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:35.290
or preparing meals, or being
able to ride on the bus,

00:47:35.290 --> 00:47:38.080
then the population mobilized.

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:42.970
The routines encouraged
people to adopt

00:47:42.970 --> 00:47:47.470
what we are calling automatic
pilot, or automatic cognition,

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:48.730
to their surroundings.

00:47:48.730 --> 00:47:51.370
But when routines
are disrupted, people

00:47:51.370 --> 00:47:54.220
began to explore and
try to figure out

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:58.990
what it was in the environment
that was disrupting it.

00:47:58.990 --> 00:48:02.620
So in these cases,
familiar routines

00:48:02.620 --> 00:48:05.500
combined with
automatic cognition

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:10.450
to restrict the attention
to the pollution.

00:48:10.450 --> 00:48:12.790
So that's a second example.

00:48:12.790 --> 00:48:19.150
Third example, in a study
of political commitments,

00:48:19.150 --> 00:48:23.320
Martin and Desmond found
that when citizens identify

00:48:23.320 --> 00:48:27.310
themselves as having strong
political commitments

00:48:27.310 --> 00:48:31.480
along a continuum from
liberal to conservative,

00:48:31.480 --> 00:48:34.480
so if they were strong
at one end or the other

00:48:34.480 --> 00:48:39.190
of the political spectrum,
they spent less time evaluating

00:48:39.190 --> 00:48:41.740
the evidence about politics.

00:48:41.740 --> 00:48:46.600
The ideological commitments
organized the world for them.

00:48:46.600 --> 00:48:49.300
And it made it
effortless and efficient

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:53.860
to know how to interpret
and how to make decisions.

00:48:53.860 --> 00:48:59.590
In a study of social
movements, the scholars

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:05.620
found that when movement leaders
use everyday metaphors, that is

00:49:05.620 --> 00:49:08.740
ordinary language,
in particular ways,

00:49:08.740 --> 00:49:12.610
they generate more
or less support.

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:19.160
So for example, the right
to life movement came up,

00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:21.340
that is an
anti-abortion movement,

00:49:21.340 --> 00:49:25.180
came up with a simple
phrase, right to life.

00:49:25.180 --> 00:49:30.160
And that had more
salience than did choice

00:49:30.160 --> 00:49:32.560
for those who were pro-abortion.

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:36.520
And so the metaphors
aligned with a whole set

00:49:36.520 --> 00:49:37.950
of other metaphors.

00:49:37.950 --> 00:49:42.000
So that people
thought more or less

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:45.480
about the process of abortion.

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:50.880
OK, the same thing with
faith-based labor movements.

00:49:50.880 --> 00:49:53.970
In the 19th century,
Mark Steinberg

00:49:53.970 --> 00:49:57.300
has written about the
ways in which the cotton

00:49:57.300 --> 00:50:00.840
workers in England were
able to mobilize and form

00:50:00.840 --> 00:50:04.740
a union because,
this is in the 1830s

00:50:04.740 --> 00:50:09.810
to '50s, because they used
the already existing language

00:50:09.810 --> 00:50:12.240
of abolition against slavery.

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:18.210
And they identified their work
in the cotton mills as slavery.

00:50:18.210 --> 00:50:21.390
And by associating
themselves with slavery,

00:50:21.390 --> 00:50:25.020
people didn't pay as much
attention to the differences

00:50:25.020 --> 00:50:29.040
and were more likely to
support and join the unions.

00:50:29.040 --> 00:50:33.240
More recent research
along this issue

00:50:33.240 --> 00:50:39.870
of the metaphors, the signaling,
this is about signaling,

00:50:39.870 --> 00:50:45.450
the metaphors that affect
deliberate or automatic

00:50:45.450 --> 00:50:52.410
cognition, a study of the
Serbo-Croatian conflict

00:50:52.410 --> 00:51:00.270
in the 1990s showed
that the associations

00:51:00.270 --> 00:51:05.520
with the past that people used
affected the level of conflict.

00:51:05.520 --> 00:51:09.720
Particular words and metaphors
generated associations

00:51:09.720 --> 00:51:10.920
with the past.

00:51:10.920 --> 00:51:14.130
So that people viewed
the current conflict

00:51:14.130 --> 00:51:18.810
as a continuation of hundreds
of years of conflict,

00:51:18.810 --> 00:51:21.540
rather than assess
the current conflict

00:51:21.540 --> 00:51:23.970
within current conditions.

00:51:23.970 --> 00:51:30.870
So simple metaphors
associations encourage

00:51:30.870 --> 00:51:36.340
people to think deliberately
or to act automatically.

00:51:36.340 --> 00:51:39.600
So finally, the last
example of these differences

00:51:39.600 --> 00:51:42.630
between automatic and
deliberate cognition

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:44.790
comes from work on narrative.

00:51:44.790 --> 00:51:46.590
So we've gone, I
just want you to see,

00:51:46.590 --> 00:51:51.510
from routines, to
disruptive habits,

00:51:51.510 --> 00:51:57.240
to language organizing
social movements and wars.

00:51:57.240 --> 00:52:02.010
And now we have, from
metaphors, we go to narratives.

00:52:02.010 --> 00:52:04.530
So researchers have
not only looked

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:07.620
at these routines,
metaphors, analogies,

00:52:07.620 --> 00:52:11.820
for triggering automatic rather
than deliberate cognition,

00:52:11.820 --> 00:52:15.600
but also at the structure,
how the metaphors are

00:52:15.600 --> 00:52:19.630
organized into a story at
narrative and storytelling.

00:52:19.630 --> 00:52:21.690
Some of the very
best research on this

00:52:21.690 --> 00:52:23.790
has been done in courtrooms.

00:52:23.790 --> 00:52:28.540
So that if witnesses
tell a story

00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:35.520
and they leave out little links
in the sequence of action,

00:52:35.520 --> 00:52:38.760
the audience, the
jurors, and the judges

00:52:38.760 --> 00:52:43.020
are more likely to
fill in those ellipses

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:46.020
with conventional action.

00:52:46.020 --> 00:52:50.820
That is what usually is
done in those circumstances.

00:52:50.820 --> 00:52:55.200
And it is most often to the
disadvantage of a defendant,

00:52:55.200 --> 00:52:59.820
because the defendant is arguing
that this was not routine.

00:52:59.820 --> 00:53:02.130
But this was unusual.

00:53:02.130 --> 00:53:05.520
So witnessing, in
criminal courts,

00:53:05.520 --> 00:53:10.710
makes a difference how
complete your narrative is.

00:53:10.710 --> 00:53:13.620
If it is not, then
people automatically

00:53:13.620 --> 00:53:16.980
fill in with
routinized information.

00:53:16.980 --> 00:53:24.780
In my own work, I have shown
that when a story describes

00:53:24.780 --> 00:53:26.850
or fails to describe--
let me put it

00:53:26.850 --> 00:53:30.870
this way, when a story fails
to describe how power is

00:53:30.870 --> 00:53:35.610
organized, people are less
likely to resist the power

00:53:35.610 --> 00:53:38.010
of that organization or person.

00:53:38.010 --> 00:53:42.990
But when a story reveals
who holds power and why,

00:53:42.990 --> 00:53:46.680
then people are more
likely to resist authority.

00:53:46.680 --> 00:53:50.400
So a little bit
of, perhaps, what

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:53.280
was happening last spring
in the Middle East.

00:53:53.280 --> 00:53:58.260
As stories circulated on
the internet about what

00:53:58.260 --> 00:54:00.630
was happening in
different places,

00:54:00.630 --> 00:54:04.200
in villages and towns
in Libya and in Egypt,

00:54:04.200 --> 00:54:05.910
those stories spread.

00:54:05.910 --> 00:54:08.970
And they told stories,
they were stories,

00:54:08.970 --> 00:54:13.140
about what the government
was doing to whom.

00:54:13.140 --> 00:54:17.100
And it helped to
mobilize the people.

00:54:17.100 --> 00:54:21.390
So that's what cognitive
science is telling us

00:54:21.390 --> 00:54:27.730
about how people make deliberate
or automatic decisions.

00:54:27.730 --> 00:54:30.880
We have some
experimental data that

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:34.330
helps us to understand
how decisions

00:54:34.330 --> 00:54:39.350
can be made specifically
about energy consumption.

