01:05:29.973 --> 01:05:32.265
PROFESSOR: Back in the '60s,
there were a lot of rebels

01:05:32.265 --> 01:05:34.420
all together.

01:05:34.420 --> 01:05:37.000
SUSAN SILBEY: All
wanting to be different.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:37.940
That's the problem.

01:05:37.940 --> 01:05:39.320
It's social.

01:05:39.320 --> 01:05:40.640
It's not individual.

01:05:40.640 --> 01:05:43.090
That's the issue.

01:05:43.090 --> 01:05:44.410
Yes, Scott?

01:05:44.410 --> 01:05:48.310
AUDIENCE: Somebody pointed out
earlier that someone might not

01:05:48.310 --> 01:05:49.570
want to reuse a towel.

01:05:49.570 --> 01:05:52.030
Because they think that
I'm only one person,

01:05:52.030 --> 01:05:53.030
what's this going to do?

01:05:53.030 --> 01:05:56.620
But I think if you have the
info that, oh, well, everyone

01:05:56.620 --> 01:05:58.630
in this room is using a towel.

01:05:58.630 --> 01:06:00.760
So that you think, oh, if
I'm the one person who's

01:06:00.760 --> 01:06:03.160
not doing it, then, I
am making a difference,

01:06:03.160 --> 01:06:04.510
but it's in a bad way.

01:06:04.510 --> 01:06:07.090
So if you contribute
to it, then you're

01:06:07.090 --> 01:06:08.560
helping make a difference.

01:06:08.560 --> 01:06:11.110
Whereas, it's not you're
just thinking, oh, well,

01:06:11.110 --> 01:06:14.780
one person what's
that going to do?

01:06:14.780 --> 01:06:20.060
SUSAN SILBEY: All right, so what
other norms or incentives might

01:06:20.060 --> 01:06:23.100
we use for energy efficient--

01:06:23.100 --> 01:06:24.410
Oh, let me see.

01:06:24.410 --> 01:06:26.630
Let's take the takeaway
message and then consider

01:06:26.630 --> 01:06:28.050
some alternative.

01:06:28.050 --> 01:06:31.700
So what this cognitive
science research

01:06:31.700 --> 01:06:34.160
and the experimental
research shows

01:06:34.160 --> 01:06:38.990
is that people do follow
the norms of others

01:06:38.990 --> 01:06:42.320
with whom they feel associated,
even if that association

01:06:42.320 --> 01:06:46.040
doesn't seem, on the
outside, terribly meaningful

01:06:46.040 --> 01:06:48.470
as some group identity.

01:06:48.470 --> 01:06:51.770
And in some
circumstances, individuals

01:06:51.770 --> 01:06:57.350
follow norms of a meaningless
and unimportant identity

01:06:57.350 --> 01:07:01.400
rather than a meaningful and
important one if the connection

01:07:01.400 --> 01:07:05.840
is based on an uncommon
characteristic, which is maybe

01:07:05.840 --> 01:07:08.390
helps Andrew's
point a little bit,

01:07:08.390 --> 01:07:11.030
that this is a
smaller group, it's

01:07:11.030 --> 01:07:13.730
an uncommon characteristic.

01:07:13.730 --> 01:07:16.910
And it's the same as Jacob,
and Ovema, and Everson.

01:07:16.910 --> 01:07:20.210
So I can identify
with this group.

01:07:20.210 --> 01:07:26.750
Now, maybe if they
had some other sign,

01:07:26.750 --> 01:07:28.160
they could have done better.

01:07:28.160 --> 01:07:31.580
Have you got any suggestions
of what other norms

01:07:31.580 --> 01:07:33.890
they might try to invoke?

01:07:36.860 --> 01:07:40.715
How might you get people,
if not only in towel reuse?

01:07:44.760 --> 01:07:47.790
How can we get people?

01:07:47.790 --> 01:07:49.260
Yes, Sid.

01:07:49.260 --> 01:07:51.180
AUDIENCE: Give them a
financial statistic,

01:07:51.180 --> 01:07:52.960
nothing coming to me.

01:07:52.960 --> 01:07:55.260
If I have like a number
or something, telling me,

01:07:55.260 --> 01:08:00.120
how much choice A, why choice
is better than choice B.

01:08:00.120 --> 01:08:01.740
SUSAN SILBEY: Tell
them how much?

01:08:01.740 --> 01:08:04.418
AUDIENCE: Well, I tell them
how much they're saving.

01:08:04.418 --> 01:08:06.210
SUSAN SILBEY: Well,
now that's interesting.

01:08:06.210 --> 01:08:10.110
Because there was a
story in the news.

01:08:10.110 --> 01:08:11.790
Remember the story
about there was

01:08:11.790 --> 01:08:15.210
a story about how
the hotels were only

01:08:15.210 --> 01:08:19.470
doing this to save money, that
they weren't, in fact, saving

01:08:19.470 --> 01:08:21.090
energy.

01:08:21.090 --> 01:08:24.010
And that had a negative effect.

01:08:24.010 --> 01:08:24.899
So it has to be--

01:08:24.899 --> 01:08:27.060
AUDIENCE: I don't mean
in this, hotel instance,

01:08:27.060 --> 01:08:31.470
I mean when you're just
talking about energy saving.

01:08:31.470 --> 01:08:33.420
if you can find that
discrepancy and you

01:08:33.420 --> 01:08:39.707
can show that choice A is energy
efficient and is saving you--

01:08:39.707 --> 01:08:41.790
SUSAN SILBEY: So you're
arguing that if you put it

01:08:41.790 --> 01:08:44.069
into dollars,
people will behave.

01:08:44.069 --> 01:08:46.859
AUDIENCE: I mean, for me, a
dollar amount says a lot more

01:08:46.859 --> 01:08:50.010
than, perhaps, trying
to I guess group

01:08:50.010 --> 01:08:53.240
me into one group or the other.

01:08:53.240 --> 01:08:54.240
SUSAN SILBEY: That sign?

01:08:56.819 --> 01:08:58.620
It's not too clear.

01:08:58.620 --> 01:09:01.590
But it's how many
miles per gallon

01:09:01.590 --> 01:09:04.590
you'll get is the car stickers.

01:09:04.590 --> 01:09:08.040
So if you by one
car, in city driving,

01:09:08.040 --> 01:09:10.600
you'll get 18 miles per gallon.

01:09:10.600 --> 01:09:13.425
But on the other car, you'll
get 23 miles per gallon.

01:09:16.149 --> 01:09:19.990
Will you buy the car
with the 23 and the 30?

01:09:19.990 --> 01:09:22.995
Is that kind of number helpful?

01:09:22.995 --> 01:09:23.620
AUDIENCE: Sure.

01:09:27.428 --> 01:09:29.470
AUDIENCE: To kind of bounce
off waht he's saying,

01:09:29.470 --> 01:09:31.060
it's a number, but
it doesn't really

01:09:31.060 --> 01:09:33.550
tell you dollars and cents.

01:09:33.550 --> 01:09:35.177
Oh, bigger number is better.

01:09:35.177 --> 01:09:36.760
SUSAN SILBEY: So you
think that should

01:09:36.760 --> 01:09:44.109
say you will save $500
this year on your gasoline,

01:09:44.109 --> 01:09:47.710
on an average of 10,000 miles
a year or something like that?

01:09:53.220 --> 01:09:53.720
Yeah?

01:09:53.720 --> 01:09:56.180
AUDIENCE: And I think
it's important that you

01:09:56.180 --> 01:09:57.937
talking about their savings.

01:09:57.937 --> 01:09:59.520
But that kind of
sounds like the stuff

01:09:59.520 --> 01:10:03.800
that you were saying before, how
people act, they might have--

01:10:03.800 --> 01:10:08.490
habitually or
traditionally and perhaps

01:10:08.490 --> 01:10:11.040
the willingness to
change their habits

01:10:11.040 --> 01:10:15.252
is not as great as
the willingness to--

01:10:15.252 --> 01:10:17.210
SUSAN SILBEY: And so why
do people buy Priuses?

01:10:21.180 --> 01:10:22.650
Yeah, Matt.

01:10:22.650 --> 01:10:25.690
AUDIENCE: I think it's talks
to the point about style

01:10:25.690 --> 01:10:27.330
and a need for individuality.

01:10:27.330 --> 01:10:31.290
That people have
Priuses because they

01:10:31.290 --> 01:10:33.430
think that they're
environmentally friendly,

01:10:33.430 --> 01:10:34.593
but they also want--

01:10:34.593 --> 01:10:36.990
SUSAN SILBEY: Everybody
else to think they are.

01:10:36.990 --> 01:10:38.550
So it's not individuality.

01:10:38.550 --> 01:10:41.400
Let's just get the terminology
clear, because it's--

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:43.710
because we talk about
individuals a lot.

01:10:43.710 --> 01:10:45.150
People buy Priuses.

01:10:45.150 --> 01:10:47.490
And what you're trying
to say is because they

01:10:47.490 --> 01:10:51.060
want to be seen to
be environmentally?

01:10:51.060 --> 01:10:51.810
No?

01:10:51.810 --> 01:10:54.310
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but in a way
that makes them look effortless

01:10:54.310 --> 01:10:55.450
like they're doing it.

01:10:55.450 --> 01:10:57.480
SUSAN SILBEY: Because
it's just routine.

01:10:57.480 --> 01:10:58.770
I've made a commitment.

01:10:58.770 --> 01:11:01.690
I'm a good person.

01:11:01.690 --> 01:11:03.650
Jessica, and then Charles.

01:11:03.650 --> 01:11:05.650
AUDIENCE: It's got to be
coupled with you go in,

01:11:05.650 --> 01:11:11.075
and you see something that's
